      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl5",
      "rationale": "CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R2) operates under a documented software quality assurance plan conforming to FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and ISO 9001:2015. Version control via Git with tagged release 2023R2.3. Full regression test suite (847 test cases) executed and passed prior to this analysis. Solver verification against ASME V&V 20 benchmark cases documented. SQA plan reviewed and approved by quality assurance team. Achieved level 5 exceeds MRL 5 requirement of level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/code-verification-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification performed via Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for all governing equation terms: incompressible Navier-Stokes, k-omega SST turbulence closure, and passive scalar hemolysis transport. Observed order of accuracy matches theoretical order (2nd-order) to within 2% across all terms. MMS results archived in verification report VR-2024-001. Independent verification by second analyst confirmed results. Achieved level 5 satisfies and exceeds MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation performed on three systematically refined meshes with refinement ratio r=2 (4M, 16M, 64M cells). GCI for primary hemolysis QoI on fine mesh: 3.1%. Observed order of convergence 1.87 is within acceptable range of theoretical second-order (1.8–2.2). Temporal discretization error assessed separately via time-step refinement study; temporal GCI < 1.5%. Combined discretization uncertainty incorporated into Monte Carlo UQ ensemble. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions documented with full traceability: blood analog fluid (glycerol-water 36% by mass, viscosity 3.5 ± 0.1 mPa·s at 37°C), pump geometry per FDA generic pump specification (Hariharan et al. 2011), flow rates and rotational speeds calibrated and traceable to NIST standards. Temperature controlled to 37 ± 0.5°C throughout testing. Five operating points (3, 4.5, 6 L/min at 2500, 3500 RPM combinations) fully characterized. Measurement uncertainty budgets provided for all controlled variables. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using validation metric V = (|E| - U_val) / U_sim where E is prediction error, U_val is experimental uncertainty, and U_sim is simulation uncertainty. Metric V < 1.0 at all five operating points for hemolysis QoI, indicating model predictions are consistent with experimental data within combined uncertainties. Velocity field comparison via normalized RMSE: 4.2% mean across measurement planes. Pressure rise comparison: within 3.8% at all operating points. Formal validation metric documented in validation report VR-2024-002. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is the direct clinical decision variable; no surrogate QoIs used. NIH computed via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories, directly matching the in-vitro measurement methodology. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, exposure time histogram) are mechanistically linked to NIH and provide additional physiological relevance. Clinical threshold (NIH < 0.005 g/100L) is the regulatory acceptance criterion per ISO 10993-4. QoI relevance is maximal — no translation required between computational and clinical quantities. Achieved level 5 exceeds MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the same geometry as the COU device. Operating conditions span the full clinical operating envelope (2500–3500 RPM, 3–6 L/min). Blood analog fluid properties matched to physiological blood rheology at 37°C. Validation dataset is independent of model calibration data. Spatial and temporal resolution of validation experiments sufficient to resolve hemolysis-relevant flow features (tip clearance vortex, blade wake). Validation domain covers all five COU operating points without extrapolation. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence verified by monitoring residuals to below 1×10^-6 for all equations and confirming mass imbalance < 0.01%. QoI monitors (NIH, pressure rise, torque) tracked over iterations to confirm stationary convergence. Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic (64-bit IEEE 754); machine epsilon effects negligible relative to discretization error. Linear solver tolerance set to 1×10^-8; solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty < 0.1% of discretization error. Documented in numerical error report NE-2024-001. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Analysis performed under a documented simulation workflow with mandatory peer review checkpoints at mesh generation, boundary condition specification, solver setup, and post-processing stages. Independent analyst review completed at each checkpoint with documented sign-off. Boundary conditions verified against experimental measurements (inlet velocity profiles measured by PIV). Post-processing scripts version-controlled and independently validated against manual calculations for three representative cases. User qualification records on file for all analysts. No use errors identified during review process. Achieved level 4 exceeds MRL 5 requirement of level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Model form assessment addresses three sub-models: (1) turbulence closure — k-omega SST selected based on systematic comparison of five RANS models against FDA pump PIV data; SST showed lowest velocity field RMSE (4.2%) and best tip-clearance vortex resolution; (2) hemolysis power-law — Giersiepen-Wurzinger model selected; applicability range (shear stress 0–400 Pa, exposure time 0.001–700 s) covers 98.7% of Lagrangian particle trajectories in COU operating envelope; (3) blood rheology — Newtonian approximation validated for shear rates > 100 s^-1 dominant in pump; non-Newtonian correction sensitivity < 2% on NIH. Model form uncertainty quantified and included in UQ ensemble. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5",
      "rationale": "All 12 model input parameters characterized with full probability distributions for Monte Carlo UQ: blood viscosity (Normal, μ=3.5 mPa·s, σ=0.1 mPa·s, from 50-sample rheometry dataset), blood density (Normal, μ=1056 kg/m³, σ=8 kg/m³), hemolysis power-law coefficients C and α (joint lognormal from Giersiepen et al. calibration data with correlation structure), pump geometry tolerances (Uniform ±0.05 mm per manufacturing spec), inlet velocity profile shape parameters (empirical distribution from 20 PIV realizations), rotational speed uncertainty (Normal, σ=5 RPM from encoder calibration), and fluid temperature (Uniform ±0.5°C). Input distributions traceable to primary measurement sources. Sobol analysis confirms input characterization captures dominant uncertainty sources. Achieved level 5 exceeds MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-mrl5",
      "rationale": "In-vitro hemolysis testing performed on n=6 pump specimens per operating point following ASTM F1841 modified protocol. Sample size determined by power analysis (β=0.80, α=0.05) to detect 20% difference in NIH. Specimens selected from production-representative manufacturing batch with dimensional inspection confirming conformance to FDA generic pump geometry within tolerance. Blood analog preparation standardized (bovine blood, standardized hematocrit 30±1%, standardized preparation protocol). Inter-specimen variability characterized; coefficient of variation < 8% for NIH across all specimens. Experimental uncertainty propagated into validation metric calculation. Achieved level 4 exceeds MRL 5 requirement of level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Equivalency assessment performed via structured comparison table mapping each experimental input parameter to its computational counterpart. Fluid viscosity: experimental 3.5 mPa·s matched in simulation to within measurement uncertainty. Pump geometry: CAD model derived from coordinate measurement machine (CMM) scan of test specimen; dimensional deviation < 0.03 mm RMS. Rotational speed: simulation value matched to tachometer-measured value ±2 RPM. Inlet boundary condition: CFD inlet velocity profile derived directly from PIV measurements at pump inlet plane. Operating pressure: outlet boundary condition set to time-averaged static pressure from experimental measurement. All equivalency assessments documented in equivalency report EQ-2024-001 with quantitative deviation metrics. Meets MRL 5 requirement at level 4."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The Morrison COU2 credibility assessment for CFD-based absolute hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under VAD operating conditions is accepted at Model Risk Level 5. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed, and achieved levels meet or exceed required levels in every case. Specifically: Software quality assurance (achieved 5, required 4), Numerical code verification (achieved 5, required 4), Discretization error (achieved 4, required 4), Test conditions (achieved 4, required 4), Output comparison (achieved 4, required 4), Relevance of QoI (achieved 5, required 4), Relevance of validation activities (achieved 4, required 4), Numerical solver error (achieved 4, required 4), Use error (achieved 4, required 3), Model form (achieved 4, required 4), Model inputs (achieved 5, required 4), Test samples (achieved 4, required 3), Equivalency of input parameters (achieved 4, required 4). The validation metric V < 1.0 at all five COU operating points confirms model predictions are consistent with experimental hemolysis measurements within combined simulation and experimental uncertainties. Monte Carlo UQ (10,000 runs) demonstrates that the 95th percentile NIH prediction remains below the clinical threshold of 0.005 g/100L across the full operating envelope, providing adequate safety margin even under adverse uncertainty combinations. Global Sobol sensitivity analysis confirms that the dominant uncertainty contributors (blood viscosity, hemolysis power-law exponent, inlet velocity profile) are well-characterized and their contributions bounded. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through validation activities to credibility factor assessments is complete and traceable. Independent peer review of all analysis steps has been completed with no unresolved findings. The computational model is accepted as sufficiently credible for its intended use: supporting regulatory submission for a Class III VAD device based on CFD-predicted absolute hemolysis levels.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
